br />We tend to put "cond_resched()" (and particularly<br />"cond_resched_lock()") in some fairly awkward places, and it's not<br />always entirely clear that task-&gt;state == TASK_RUNNING there.<br /><br />So the preemptive behavior of not *really* putting the task to sleep<br />may actually be the right one. But it is rather non-intuitive given<br />the name - because "cond_resched()" basically is not at all equivalent<br />to "if (need_resched()) schedule()", which you'd kind of expect.<br /><br />An explicit schedule will actually act on the task-&gt;state, and make us<br />go to sleep. "cond_resched()"  really is just a "voluntary preemption<br />point". And I think it would be better if it got named that way.<br /><br />            Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
